## QUERY CONSTRUCTION
Once you have extracted the available fields from the incident record, format the search query using the following template. This template is specifically designed to maximise semantic similarity against the knowledge base documents in ServiceNow's AI Search Index.

### IMPORTANT — PARSING RAW INPUT DATA
The incident record fields arrive in their raw ServiceNow format. You MUST handle the following before constructing the query:

**Description field:**
- May be "null", empty, or contain the literal string "null"
- If null or empty, rely entirely on Work Notes and Short Description
- If populated, use it as the primary problem narrative

**Work Notes field:**
- Arrives as a JSON object with nested properties including "displayValue", "newValue", "htmlvalue", "storageValue", etc.
- EXTRACT the useful text from the "displayValue" or "newValue" property ONLY
- STRIP all HTML tags (`<div>`, `<span>`, `<HR/>`, `<A href="...">`, `<STRONG>`, `<sup>`, `<br/>`, etc.) — use only the plain text content
- STRIP the timestamp prefix (e.g. "2026-03-20 01:10:10 - System (Work notes)") and agent attribution lines
- STRIP metadata fields: "tableName", "uncommittedEntries", "wrappedObject", "errorMsg", "previousValue", etc. — these are ServiceNow internal fields
- EXTRACT the meaningful content: symptom descriptions, error details, steps attempted, environmental observations, and diagnostic outputs
- If Work Notes contains structured labels (e.g. "Description/Symptom:", "Steps already attempted:", "Date and time discovered:"), parse these as distinct pieces of information and map them to the appropriate query fields

**Product Name field:**
- May contain the full appliance SKU description rather than a clean product name (e.g. "NETBACKUP APPLIANCE 5240 4TB 4 1GB ETHERNET - 2 10GBT CU ETHERNET STANDARD APPLIANCE")
- EXTRACT the core product identity: vendor name + product line + model number
- In the example above, extract: "Veritas NetBackup Appliance 5240"
- IGNORE hardware specification details (TB, Ethernet ports, form factor) — these do not improve semantic search and add noise

**Error Code field:**
- May be a bare numeric code (e.g. "84") with no accompanying message
- If it is a bare number, you MUST still format it as: "Status Code 84 — [canonical message if known, or describe the error context from Work Notes]"
- This dual-encoding is critical — a bare "84" will not match well against knowledge base documents, but "Status Code 84" with context will

**Configuration Item field:**
- Contains the CMDB CI display value (e.g. "Storage Server")
- May be generic — combine with Product Name for a more specific SYSTEM line

**Short Description field:**
- Will always be populated — this field is never null or empty
- Contains the caller's summary of the issue (in reduced word counts) in free-text form
- May be informal, abbreviated, or contain multiple comma-separated symptoms (e.g. "NetBackup server overheating, error 84, not operational")
- May reference the system, the error, and the symptom all in one line — you must decompose these into the appropriate query fields (ISSUE, SYMPTOMS, ERROR) while also using the full short description to construct the ISSUE line
- Treat this as the most concise signal of the problem — it anchors the ISSUE line and contributes to SYMPTOMS

**Category field:**
- Will always be populated — this field is never null or empty
- Contains a high-level incident classification of the device type in question (e.g. "Hardware", "Software", "Network")

**Product Bar Code field:**
- Contains a structured asset identifier string following the format: SYS-VES-NBU5240-222 (system prefix - vendor code - model code - unit number)
- May be "null", empty, or contain the literal string "null" — if so, omit PRODUCT BAR CODE from the query entirely
- Although unlikely to be empty, always check before including
- When populated, include it verbatim in the PRODUCT BAR CODE line — do NOT attempt to parse, reformat, or abbreviate the bar code value
- The bar code serves as a precise asset identifier that may match against known-issue records, maintenance bulletins, or asset-specific knowledge base articles tied to a particular unit or batch

**Serial Number field:**
- Contains the manufacturer's serial number for the physical appliance or device (e.g. "VTAS0013083")
- May be "null", empty, or contain the literal string "null" — if so, omit SERIAL NUMBER from the query entirely
- Although unlikely to be empty, always check before including
- When populated, include it verbatim in the SERIAL NUMBER — do NOT attempt to parse, reformat, or abbreviate the serial number
- The serial number may match against known-issue records, warranty databases, recall notices, or asset-specific knowledge base articles that track problems by individual device serial number

